The **Paul-Bunnell test** detects **heterophile antibodies** (non-specific antibodies produced during infectious mononucleosis) that agglutinate sheep or horse red blood cells. These antibodies are not virus-specific but cross-react with animal antigens, forming the basis of the test. This distinguishes it from **homophile antibodies** (option C), which are virus-specific.
